Joints lo rendu tables nunchi em kavalo from ki mundhu rayali from ventane class name of 1st table joint class name of second table on same feild with = 
example :
select  s.student_id, s.last_name ,s.year,s.first_name ,c.credits,c.course_name from students s right join  courses c on s.dept=c.dept;

1. INNER JOIN
ðŸ‘‰ Takes only the common rows from both tables.
2. LEFT JOIN
ðŸ‘‰ Takes all rows from the left table, and the matching rows from the right table.
ðŸ‘‰ If no match â†’ fills with NULL.
3. RIGHT JOIN
ðŸ‘‰ Takes all rows from the right table, and the matching rows from the left table.
ðŸ‘‰ If no match â†’ fills with NULL.
4. FULL JOIN
ðŸ‘‰ Takes all rows from both tables.
ðŸ‘‰ If no match â†’ fills with NULL on the missing side.


ðŸ‘‰ Simple trick:
INNER = common only
LEFT = left all + right matched
RIGHT = right all + left matched
FULL = everything


All 4 joints :
select student_id , first_name ,course_name from students left join courses on students.dept=courses.dept; 
select s.student_id, s.last_name ,s.year, c.semester from students  s inner join courses c  on s.dept=c.dept;
select s.student_id, s.last_name ,s.year, c.semester from students  s full outer join courses c  on s.dept=c.dept;
select  s.student_id, s.last_name ,s.year,s.first_name ,c.credits,c.course_name from students s right join  courses c on s.dept=c.dept;



Adding one output result to another join  for that we use with and as:

WITH left_result AS (
    SELECT s.student_id, s.last_name, c.course_name
    FROM students s
    LEFT JOIN courses c ON s.dept = c.dept
)
SELECT lr.student_id, lr.last_name, c.course_name
FROM left_result lr
RIGHT JOIN courses c ON lr.course_name = c.course_name;
